<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">There are 3 things that define a tank class (or more appropriately in this case, Paladins and Warriors):  <p>

1. Damage Dealing.  Beyond duelwield, equal class specific 2hand weapons are slightly more powerful in a warriors hands. With similiar weapons, the warrior can add criticals to still hold an advantage. Paladins gain Undead DD spells, albeit most come to late. Finally at 49 (162dd) and 54 (273dd), they can actually match/outdamage a warriors melee ability.<br>
Frankly, I'd kill this line of spells for added melee power regardless.<p>

2. Damage Taking.  Warriors favor higher hp. While also carrying a higher ac in class specific gear. The drawback to make sure as a warrior, you have full cleric buffs up to hold this advantage. A Paladins personal buffs will comfortable surpass a warriors natural hp's and match their ac at 39, and greater still at 49+.   A feat rarely done, while most clerics are simply too stubborn to keep symbol up on all tanks (short of performing it as an hourly ritual in the planes).<p>

3. Taunting.  Tauntings purpose is to remove unwanted mobs off of casters or disabled melees. It is the Damage Taking and not Dealing that defines the tank class in order to taunt effectively.  Warriors possess a higher taunt skill cap, which enables them to have a higher chance of successfully taunting a mob to them.  Beginning at lvl 30, Paladins are no longer so reliant on the taunt skill, they gain Stuns.  A quick spell which will momentarily freeze a mob in its' place. Allowing them to control a mobs aggression from across the room or in front of them almost instantly.  At 49 and again lvl 52, the 2nd and 3rd line of stuns are added to the arsenal. Rapidly casting all 3 in unison can freeze a mob permanently (not to mention rendering it unable to cast) until its death, without the tanks taking damage.<p>

These are the tangibles. Upto lvl 30, Paladins fall short in all 3 categories. After lvl 30 and particularly after 40,50, in certain circumstances Paladins can mildly gain similiar traits as warriors in the 1st two areas listed. But will struggle.  After 50, Paladins will hold the title if nothing else, Taunter and primary/backup tank.<p>

Unfortunately those 3 areas described, embodies warriors.  Paladins receive intangibles such as healing, loh, root/enstill, and soothe/pacify of note. After 40 and 50 typically the perfect group includes 1 enchanter then 1 cleric.  You can fill in the gaps later.<br>
Pulling will belong to a monk/sk if you have 1.  Warriors have ac/hp and higher MR for pulling, Paladins have Pacify and root/enstill to comfortably counteract. its a give and take.<p>

Huron<br>
54 Cavalier<br>
Sol Ro</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
